---
/**
 * CIDR / Subnet Checker — the cidr-checker tool page (SEO surface).
 * Paste a list of IPs/CIDRs; get the minimal covering set, overlaps and
 * containment, and a parsed breakdown — entirely in the browser.
 */
import Shell from '../components/Shell.astro';
import CidrCheckerPlayground from '../components/CidrCheckerPlayground.astro';
import Button from '../components/Button.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import ToolHero from '../components/ToolHero.astro';
import ToolGapVisual from '../components/ToolGapVisual.astro';
import ToolPipeline from '../components/ToolPipeline.astro';
import FaqList from '../components/FaqList.astro';
import ToolCrossLinks from '../components/ToolCrossLinks.astro';
import { site, navLinks } from '../data/site';
import { getTool } from '../data/tools';
import { softwareAppLd, faqPageLd } from '../lib/jsonld';

const tool = getTool('cidr-checker');
const pagePath = '/cidr-checker';
const pageUrl = `${site.url}${pagePath}`;

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'What does the CIDR / Subnet Checker do?',
    a: 'Paste a list of IPs or CIDRs — one per line — and it does three things: aggregates them into the minimal set of CIDR blocks that exactly covers the same addresses, reports every overlap and containment between the entries, and shows a parsed, normalised breakdown of each line. Everything runs in your browser.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Does my list ever leave my browser?',
    a: 'No. Parsing, comparison and aggregation all run 100% client-side in your tab — no server, no account, no logging. You can safely paste internal allow-lists and route tables.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What does “aggregation” mean here?',
    a: 'Aggregation (also called summarisation or supernetting) replaces several adjacent or overlapping blocks with the fewest CIDRs that cover exactly the same addresses — for example 192.168.0.0/24 through 192.168.3.0/24 collapses to a single 192.168.0.0/22. It shortens firewall rules and route tables without changing what they match.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What is the difference between overlap and containment?',
    a: 'Containment means one block sits entirely inside another (10.0.5.0/24 is inside 10.0.0.0/16). A plain overlap means two blocks share some addresses without one fully enclosing the other. The checker labels each relationship — equal, contains, inside, or overlaps — so you can spot redundant or conflicting entries.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Does it handle IPv6 and mixed lists?',
    a: 'Yes. IPv4 and IPv6 entries are parsed together; comparison and aggregation are done within each family (a v4 block and a v6 block never overlap), and the minimal covering set is reported per family using full 128-bit precision for IPv6.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What input does it accept?',
    a: 'One IP or CIDR per line. A bare address is treated as a /32 (or /128). Blank lines and lines starting with # are ignored, so you can paste a commented config block directly. Anything that is not a valid IP or CIDR is flagged rather than silently dropped.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How do I check if two subnets overlap?',
    a: 'Each CIDR is converted to its first and last address as a numeric range. Two CIDRs overlap when their ranges share any address — even a single one. Paste your list into the tool and every overlapping or contained pair is labelled automatically, distinguishing equal blocks, one-inside-the-other (containment), and partial overlaps.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How do I find the minimal covering set of a list of CIDRs?',
    a: 'Paste the full list and the tool sorts the entries, merges adjacent and overlapping ranges into contiguous numeric intervals, then re-splits each interval into the fewest aligned CIDR blocks that cover it exactly. The result is the smallest possible set of CIDRs that still covers every address in the original list — useful for shrinking routing tables, firewall rules, and BGP prefix lists.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How do I check for overlapping CIDRs before AWS VPC peering or a VPN setup?',
    a: 'AWS rejects VPC peering, Transit Gateway attachments, and VPN connections when any CIDR ranges overlap. Paste all VPC and subnet CIDRs into the checker before deploying: it flags every overlapping or contained pair so you can re-plan address space ahead of time. Because everything runs in the browser, no internal IP data is uploaded.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What is the difference between subnetting and supernetting (route summarization)?',
    a: 'Subnetting splits one block into smaller subnets by lengthening the prefix — for example /24 into eight /27s. Supernetting, also called CIDR aggregation or route summarization, is the reverse: it merges multiple contiguous blocks into one larger block by shortening the prefix — for example eight /27s back into a single /24. Aggregation reduces routing-table size and firewall-rule count while preserving full address coverage.',
  },
];

const softwareApp = softwareAppLd({
  name: 'CIDR / Subnet Checker',
  description:
    'Free in-browser CIDR aggregator & subnet overlap checker. Paste a list to merge CIDR ranges, detect overlaps & find the minimal set. No signup, runs locally.',
  url: pageUrl,
  subCategory: 'Networking',
  featureList: [
    'Aggregate IPs/CIDRs into the minimal covering set',
    'Detect overlap and containment between blocks',
    'IPv4 and IPv6, aggregated per family',
    '100% client-side, no upload, no signup',
  ],
  keywords: tool?.keywords.join(', '),
});
const faqPage = faqPageLd(faqs);

const pipeline = [
  {
    title: 'Parse each line.',
    body: 'Every line is read as an IP or CIDR and normalised to its network; blanks and # comments are skipped.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Compare pairwise.',
    body: 'Each pair in the same family is checked for equality, containment or overlap and labelled.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Merge the ranges.',
    body: 'Entries become numeric intervals, sorted and merged wherever they touch or overlap.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Re-split to CIDRs.',
    body: 'Each merged interval is decomposed into the fewest aligned CIDR blocks that cover it exactly.',
  },
];

const aggregateExample = `# four adjacent /24s
192.168.0.0/24
192.168.1.0/24      →   192.168.0.0/22
192.168.2.0/24
192.168.3.0/24`;

const overlapExample = `10.0.0.0/16
10.0.5.0/24         →   10.0.0.0/16 contains 10.0.5.0/24
10.0.5.0/24         →   10.0.5.0/24 is the same block as 10.0.5.0/24`;
---

<Shell
  title="CIDR / Subnet Checker — CIDR Aggregator & Overlap Tool"
  description="Free in-browser CIDR aggregator & subnet overlap checker. Paste a list to merge CIDR ranges, detect overlaps & find the minimal set. No signup, runs locally."
  canonical="/cidr-checker"
  jsonLd={[softwareApp, faqPage]}
>
  <ToolHero
    slug="cidr-checker"
    eyebrow="CIDR / Subnet Checker · Networking"
    badges={[
      { label: 'Runs in your browser', variant: 'live' },
      { label: 'IPv4 & IPv6', variant: 'neutral' },
      { label: 'No signup', variant: 'neutral' },
    ]}
  >
    <Fragment slot="headline">Aggregate CIDRs and catch overlaps.</Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="lead">
      Paste a list of IPs/CIDRs to get the minimal covering set, every overlap and containment, and
      a parsed breakdown of each line — all in your browser.
    </Fragment>
  </ToolHero>

  <section id="playground" class="scroll-mt-24 bg-canvas-soft pt-8 pb-20 sm:pb-24">
    <div class="container-page">
      <h2 class="sr-only">CIDR / Subnet Checker playground</h2>
      <CidrCheckerPlayground />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="why" class="scroll-mt-24 border-t border-hairline bg-canvas">
    <div class="container-page py-16 sm:py-20">
      <div class="mx-auto grid max-w-5xl gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[0.9fr_1.1fr] lg:gap-16">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">The Gap</p>
          <h2 class="display-lg mt-3 text-balance text-ink">
            Sprawling rules hide overlaps and dead entries.
          </h2>
          <ToolGapVisual />
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <p class="body-md text-pretty text-body">
            Security groups, route tables and allow-lists accumulate CIDRs over time. Soon two
            entries overlap, one is fully inside another, or four adjacent blocks could have been a
            single line. Eyeballing that across dozens of ranges is exactly where mistakes hide —
            and finding overlapping CIDR ranges in a large list by hand is error-prone even for
            experienced engineers.
          </p>
          <p class="body-md text-pretty text-body">
            This checker reads the whole list at once: it flags every overlap and containment, and
            collapses the set into the fewest CIDRs that cover the same addresses. Cleaner rules,
            fewer surprises — and a reliable pre-flight check before AWS VPC peering or any setup
            where overlapping ranges cause hard failures. Runs entirely in the browser, with nothing
            to install.
          </p>
          <p class="body-sm text-mute">
            Need to inspect a single block? Open the
            <a class="link-inline" href="/subnet-calculator">Subnet Calculator</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <ToolPipeline
    id="how-it-works"
    eyebrow="The Pipeline"
    heading="How it works."
    lead="Four deterministic steps run as you type — all inside your browser tab, with exact BigInt arithmetic."
    steps={pipeline}
  />

  <section id="examples" class="scroll-mt-24 border-t border-hairline bg-canvas">
    <div class="container-page py-16 sm:py-20">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-2xl text-center">
        <p class="eyebrow">By Example</p>
        <h2 class="display-lg mt-3 text-ink">Aggregate, and catch overlaps.</h2>
        <p class="body-md mx-auto mt-3 max-w-xl text-pretty text-body">
          Two of the most common jobs: collapsing contiguous blocks, and surfacing entries that
          overlap or duplicate each other.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="mx-auto mt-10 grid max-w-5xl gap-8 lg:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="min-w-0">
          <h3 class="display-sm text-ink">Aggregation</h3>
          <p class="body-sm mt-2 mb-4 text-pretty text-body">
            Adjacent blocks collapse to the minimal covering set.
          </p>
          <CodeBlock lang="text" filename="aggregate" code={aggregateExample} />
        </div>
        <div class="min-w-0">
          <h3 class="display-sm text-ink">Overlap &amp; containment</h3>
          <p class="body-sm mt-2 mb-4 text-pretty text-body">
            Redundant and enclosing entries are labelled.
          </p>
          <CodeBlock lang="text" filename="overlap" code={overlapExample} />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="next" class="scroll-mt-24 bg-inverse text-inverse-fg">
    <div class="container-page py-16 sm:py-20">
      <div class="mx-auto grid max-w-5xl items-center gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[1.1fr_0.9fr] lg:gap-16">
        <div class="min-w-0">
          <p class="eyebrow !text-cyan">Next Step</p>
          <h2 class="display-lg mt-3 text-balance text-inverse-fg">
            Inspect one of the blocks in detail.
          </h2>
          <p class="body-md mt-4 text-pretty text-white/70">
            When an entry looks off, drop it into the
            <span translate="no">Subnet Calculator</span> to see its network, broadcast, mask and
            full host range for IPv4 or IPv6 — the per-block companion to checking a whole list.
          </p>
          <div class="mt-7 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3">
            <Button href="/subnet-calculator" variant="secondary">Open the Subnet Calculator</Button>
          </div>
        </div>
        <CodeBlock
          lang="text"
          filename="result.txt"
          code={`in:   192.168.0.0/24 … /23
out:  192.168.0.0/22
note: 1 block covers all four`}
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FaqList faqs={faqs} />

  <div class="container-page py-4">
    <p class="body-sm text-mute">New to this? Read our guide on <a href="/learn/guides/networking-for-devops" class="link-inline">Networking for DevOps Engineers</a>.</p>
  </div>

  <ToolCrossLinks slug="cidr-checker">
    <Fragment slot="lead">
      The CIDR / Subnet Checker is one tool in
      <span translate="no">{site.name}</span> — a growing canopy of browser-based validators,
      converters and testers that never touch a server.
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="links">
      More networking: the
      <a class="link-inline" href="/subnet-calculator">Subnet Calculator</a>, the
      <a class="link-inline" href="/subnet-splitter">Subnet Splitter</a> for the inverse job of
      carving a block into smaller subnets, and the
      <a class="link-inline" href="/ip-address-converter">IP Address Converter</a>, or browse the
      full <a class="link-inline" href={navLinks[0].href}>tools directory</a>.
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="disclaimer">
      Provided as-is for convenience; always confirm critical network changes against your own
      authority. <span translate="no">{site.name}</span> is free and open.
    </Fragment>
  </ToolCrossLinks>
</Shell>
